│                                                              │
│ ### Analysis of the Bug                                      │
│                                                              │
│ 1.  **The Symptom:** The LLVM verifier aborts with an        │
│ "Instruction does not dominate all uses!" error. This        │
│ happens when running the `loop-unroll` pass. The error       │
│ points to a newly created LCSSA PHI node (`%load.lcssa`) and │
│ an instruction that uses it (`shl`).                         │
│ 2.  **The Context:** The reproducer has two loops. The inner │
│ loop (`loop.2`) has a trip count that depends on a value     │
│ (`%load`) computed in the outer loop (`loop.1`). When        │
│ `loop-unroll` (which uses `ScalarEvolution` and              │
│ `SCEVExpander`) tries to generate code for this symbolic     │
│ trip count, it needs to bring `%load` into the preheader of  │
│ `loop.2`. It does this by creating an LCSSA PHI node         │
│ (`%load.lcssa`) in the `if` block.                           │
│ 3.  **The Root Cause:** The `SCEVExpander` then creates      │
│ instructions to compute the trip count (like the `shl`       │
│ mentioned in the error). The root cause analysis correctly   │
│ identifies that these new instructions are being inserted at │
│ the wrong position within the basic block. The function      │
│ `GetOptimalInsertionPointForCastOf` uses                     │
│ `BB->getFirstInsertionPt()`. According to LLVM documentation │
│ and common practice, `getFirstInsertionPt()` returns an      │
│ iterator to the first non-PHI instruction. If a block        │
│ contains only PHI nodes, this points to the beginning of the │
│ instruction list. Inserting a non-PHI instruction there      │
│ places it *before* the PHI nodes, violating a fundamental IR │
│ rule: all PHI nodes must be grouped at the beginning of a    │
│ basic block. This leads to the dominance error, as the new   │
│ instruction uses a PHI that does not textually precede it.   │
│ 4.  **The Fix:** The correct insertion point for new non-PHI │
│ instructions is *after* all existing PHI nodes. The          │
│ `BasicBlock::getFirstNonPHI()` method provides an iterator   │
│ to exactly this position. Therefore, replacing               │
│ `getFirstInsertionPt()` with `getFirstNonPHI()` in the       │
│ identified location should resolve the issue.                │
│                                                              │
│ ### Proposed Fix                                             │
│                                                              │
│ I will modify the `GetOptimalInsertionPointForCastOf`        │
│ function in                                                  │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/ScalarEvolutionExpander.cpp`.     │
│                                                              │
│ -   **File:**                                                │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/ScalarEvolutionExpander.cpp`      │
│ -   **Function:**                                            │
│ `SCEVExpander::GetOptimalInsertionPointForCastOf`            │
│ -   **Change:** Replace the call to `.getFirstInsertionPt()` │
│ with `.getFirstNonPHI()`.                                    │
│                                                              │
│ This will ensure that any new instructions are inserted      │
│ after all PHI nodes in the entry block, maintaining the      │
│ integrity of the LLVM IR.                                    │
